There are, however, amid their similarity, some very remarkable differences in the substances which they contain, the trap rocks containing calcareous spar, and the lava never containing any. On the supposition that they are both of igneous origin, is there any circumstance, in the conditions in which heat may have been applied to them, which can account ior this differencei Sir james Hali, in a train of most philosophical and happily-contrived experimenta, has explained the nature of those conditione, and has shown that the presence oi calcareous spar, or the wantos it, may arise from the greater or less compression under which the fusion of the basalt was performed. This has served to explain a great difficulty in the history of the mineral kingdom.
